english:
  title: Discourse on Tiger Rock
  author: Yun Ja
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To the east of Geumcheon, a mountain rises, its form rushing northward like a prowling tiger, crowned with jagged stone. The world calls it Tiger Rock. The geomancers surveyed its shape and built a temple at its northern corner, naming it Tiger-Taming Temple. Seven li to its north stands a bridge called Bow Bridge, and ten li beyond that, a hermitage called Lion's Hermitage—all meant to suppress the tiger's restless stride.

    In the spring of GyeongO, I came to govern this place after serving as a censor. The people were naturally foolish, and I too am foolish. All said the rock was to blame, and that the temples we built were meant to restrain it, to make us less foolish.

    But I ask: why do we speak of the Madness Spring, the Lust Spring, the Greed Spring? Simply because those who drink become mad, lustful, greedy—thus earning their names. How then can we know that those dwelling beneath this rock, drinking its waters, eating its soil, wandering and sleeping here, do not become foolish for the same reason? Perhaps the principle holds. Yet perhaps it does not.

    Once, Wu Yinzhi, serving as magistrate, drank from the Greed Spring yet remained uncorrupted. His integrity burned brighter still. He wrote:

    "Though I gave the springs to righteous men to try,
    Their hearts would not bend, nor their virtue deny."

    Does not human wisdom and folly stem from the moment of our birth, beyond what mountains and waters can transform? Suppose someone dwelling in this place possessed the virtue of Yan Hui—appearing foolish yet remaining wise. Could we ever truly know?

    Considering this, my foolishness and that of the people comes not from the rock. Those who blame the rock are themselves truly foolish.

    Alas! Liu Zongyuan of Tang loved Ran Stream and made his home there, renaming it Fool's Stream. He branded it with his own foolishness—echoing the ancient spirit of Foolish Old Man Valley—yet wisdom dwelt within. True foolishness, by contrast, dwells in every word and deed, in public and private alike, wholly without escape.

    Therefore, I humbly borrow Liu Zongyuan's wisdom in naming Fool's Stream, and I rename Tiger Rock as Fool's Rock. What remedy is there for those genuinely foolish? I venture this discourse and await the judgment of the truly wise.
  footnotes:
    - Madness Spring, Lust Spring, and Greed Spring are legendary springs in classical Chinese literature believed to impart their respective qualities to those who drink from them.
    - Wu Yinzhi (吳隱之) was a historical figure known for his integrity. The poem quoted celebrates moral constancy.
    - Yan Hui was Confucius's most virtuous disciple, known for his wisdom and moral character.
    - Liu Zongyuan (柳宗元), Tang dynasty poet and official, renamed Ran Stream to Fool's Stream as a form of self-effacing humility.
    - Foolish Old Man Valley refers to an ancient narrative about an old man who attempted to move mountains through persistent labor—a story valorizing humble perseverance.
